# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: radio-access-network
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] The 3GPP specification 38 series provides the technical details behind 5G NR, the successor of LTE.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] The study of 5G NR within 3GPP started in 2015, and the first specification was made available by the end of 2017.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] While the 3GPP standardization process was ongoing, the industry had already begun efforts to implement infrastructure compliant with the draft standard, with the first large-scale commercial launch of 5G NR having occurred in the end of 2018.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Since 2019, many operators have deployed 5G NR networks and handset manufacturers have developed 5G NR enabled handsets.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] A "Non-Standalone" (NSA) gNodeB is built on an existing LTE (4G) base station (eNodeB or eNB).
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Ooredoo was the first carrier to launch a commercial 5G NR network, in May 2018 in Qatar.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Other carriers around the world have been following suit.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] In 2018, 3GPP published Release 15, which includes what is described as "Phase 1" standardization for 5G NR.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] The timeline for Release 16, which will be "5G phase 2", follows a freeze date of March 2020 and a completion date of June 2020, Release 17 was originally scheduled for delivery in September 2021. but, because of the COVID-19 pandemic, it was rescheduled for June 2022.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Rel.18 is referred to as "NR Advanced" signifying another milestone in wireless communication systems.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] NR Advanced will include features such as eXtended Reality (XR), AI/ML studies, and Mobility enhancements.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Mobility is in the core of 3GPP technology and has so far been handled on Layer 3 (RRC), now, in Rel-18 the work on mobility is to introduce lower layer triggered mobility.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Initial 5G NR launches will depend on existing LTE infrastructure in non-standalone (NSA) mode, before maturation of the standalone (SA) mode with the 5G core network.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Additionally, the spectrum can be dynamically shared between LTE and 5G NR.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] To make better use of existing assets, carriers may opt to dynamically share it between LTE and 5G NR.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] The spectrum is multiplexed over time between both generations of mobile networks depending on user demand, while still using the LTE network for control functions.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Dynamic spectrum sharing (DSS) may be deployed on existing LTE equipment as long as it is compatible with 5G NR.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Only the 5G NR terminal needs to be compatible with DSS.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] The non-standalone (NSA) mode of 5G NR refers to an option of 5G NR deployment that depends on the control plane of an existing LTE network for control functions, while 5G NR is exclusively focused on the user plane.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] This is reported to speed up 5G adoption, however some operators and vendors have criticized prioritizing the introduction of 5G NR NSA on the grounds that it could hinder the implementation of the standalone mode of the network.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] It uses the same core network as a 4G network, but with upgraded radio equipment.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] The standalone (SA) mode of 5G NR refers to using 5G cells for both signalling and information transfer, essentially a 5G network without any legacy 4G infrastructure.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] It includes the new 5G Packet Core architecture instead of relying on the 4G Evolved Packet Core, to allow the deployment of 5G without the LTE network.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] It is expected to have lower cost, better efficiency, and to assist development of new use cases.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] However, initial deployment might see slower speed than existing network due to the allocation of spectrum.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] It uses a new core network dedicated to 5G.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] The length of the cyclic prefix is inversely proportional to the subcarrier spacing.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] It is 4.7 μs with 15 kHz, and 4.7 / 16 = 0.29 μs for 240 kHz subcarrier spacing.
[src:radio-access-network/5g-nr] Additionally, higher subcarrier spacings allow for reduced latency and increased support for high-frequency bands, essential for the ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC) and enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB) applications in 5G.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Beamforming can be used for radio or sound waves.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] It has found numerous applications in radar, sonar, seismology, wireless communications, radio astronomy, acoustics and biomedicine.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Adaptive beamforming is used to detect and estimate the signal of interest at the output of a sensor array by means of optimal (e.g., least-squares) spatial filtering and interference rejection.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] To change the directionality of the array when transmitting, a beamformer controls the phase and relative amplitude of the signal at each transmitter, in order to create a pattern of constructive and destructive interference in the wavefront.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] When receiving, information from different sensors is combined in a way where the expected pattern of radiation is preferentially observed.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] The beamforming technique involves sending the pulse from each projector at slightly different times (the projector closest to the ship last), so that every pulse hits the ship at exactly the same time, producing the effect of a single strong pulse from a single powerful projector.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] The same technique can be carried out in air using loudspeakers, or in radar/radio using antennas.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Receive beamforming can also be used with microphones or radar antennas.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] With narrowband systems the time delay is equivalent to a "phase shift", so in this case the array of antennas, each one shifted a slightly different amount, is called a phased array.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] A narrow band system, typical of radars, is one where the bandwidth is only a small fraction of the center frequency.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] With wideband systems this approximation no longer holds, which is typical in sonars.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] In the receive beamformer the signal from each antenna may be amplified by a different "weight." Different weighting patterns (e.g., Dolph–Chebyshev) can be used to achieve the desired sensitivity patterns.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] A main lobe is produced together with nulls and sidelobes.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] As well as controlling the main lobe width (beamwidth) and the sidelobe levels, the position of a null can be controlled.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] This is useful to ignore noise or jammers in one particular direction, while listening for events in other directions.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] A similar result can be obtained on transmission.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] For the full mathematics on directing beams using amplitude and phase shifts, see the mathematical section in phased array.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Conventional beamformers, such as the Butler matrix, use a fixed set of weightings and time-delays (or phasings) to combine the signals from the sensors in the array, primarily using only information about the location of the sensors in space and the wave directions of interest.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] In contrast, adaptive beamforming techniques (e.g., MUSIC, SAMV) generally combine this information with properties of the signals actually received by the array, typically to improve rejection of unwanted signals from other directions.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] This process may be carried out in either the time or the frequency domain.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] As the name indicates, an adaptive beamformer is able to automatically adapt its response to different situations.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Some criterion has to be set up to allow the adaptation to proceed such as minimizing the total noise output.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Because of the variation of noise with frequency, in wide band systems it may be desirable to carry out the process in the frequency domain.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Beamforming can be computationally intensive.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Sonar phased array has a data rate low enough that it can be processed in real time in software, which is flexible enough to transmit or receive in several directions at once.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] In contrast, radar phased array has a data rate so high that it usually requires dedicated hardware processing, which is hard-wired to transmit or receive in only one direction at a time.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] However, newer field programmable gate arrays are fast enough to handle radar data in real time, and can be quickly re-programmed like software, blurring the hardware/software distinction.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Sonar beamforming utilizes a similar technique to electromagnetic beamforming, but varies considerably in implementation details.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Sonar applications vary from 1 Hz to as high as 2 MHz, and array elements may be few and large, or number in the hundreds yet very small.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] This will shift sonar beamforming design efforts significantly between demands of such system components as the "front end" (transducers, pre-amplifiers and digitizers) and the actual beamformer computational hardware downstream.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] High frequency, focused beam, multi-element imaging-search sonars and acoustic cameras often implement fifth-order spatial processing that places strains equivalent to Aegis radar demands on the processors.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Many sonar systems, such as on torpedoes, are made up of arrays of up to 100 elements that must accomplish beam steering over a 100 degree field of view and work in both active and passive modes.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Sonar arrays are used both actively and passively in 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional arrays.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Sonar differs from radar in that in some applications such as wide-area-search all directions often need to be listened to, and in some applications broadcast to, simultaneously.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] In a narrowband sonar receiver, the phases for each beam can be manipulated entirely by signal processing software, as compared to present radar systems that use hardware to 'listen' in a single direction at a time.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Sonar also uses beamforming to compensate for the significant problem of the slower propagation speed of sound as compared to that of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] In side-look-sonars, the speed of the towing system or vehicle carrying the sonar is moving at sufficient speed to move the sonar out of the field of the returning sound "ping".
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] In addition to focusing algorithms intended to improve reception, many side scan sonars also employ beam steering to look forward and backward to "catch" incoming pulses that would have been missed by a single sidelooking beam.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] The delay-and-sum beamforming technique uses multiple microphones to localize sound sources.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] One disadvantage of this technique is that adjustments of the position or of the number of microphones changes the performance of the beamformer nonlinearly.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Additionally, due to the number of combinations possible, it is computationally hard to find the best configuration.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] One of the techniques to solve this problem is the use of genetic algorithms.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Such algorithm searches for the microphone array configuration that provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for each steered orientation.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Experiments showed that such algorithm could find the best configuration of a constrained search space comprising ~33 million solutions in a matter of seconds instead of days.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Beamforming techniques used in cellular phone standards have advanced through the generations to make use of more complex systems to achieve higher density cells, with higher throughput.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] An increasing number of consumer 802.11ac Wi-Fi devices with MIMO capability can support beamforming to boost data communication rates.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] To receive (but not transmit), there is a distinction between analog and digital beamforming.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] For example, if there are 100 sensor elements, the "digital beamforming" approach entails that each of the 100 signals passes through an analog-to-digital converter to create 100 digital data streams.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Then these data streams are added up digitally, with appropriate scale-factors or phase-shifts, to get the composite signals.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] By contrast, the "analog beamforming" approach entails taking the 100 analog signals, scaling or phase-shifting them using analog methods, summing them, and then usually digitizing the *single* output data stream.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Digital beamforming has the advantage that the digital data streams (100 in this example) can be manipulated and combined in many possible ways in parallel, to get many different output signals in parallel.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] The signals from every direction can be measured simultaneously, and the signals can be integrated for a longer time when studying far-off objects and simultaneously integrated for a shorter time to study fast-moving close objects, and so on.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] This cannot be done as effectively for analog beamforming, not only because each parallel signal combination requires its own circuitry, but more fundamentally because digital data can be copied perfectly but analog data cannot.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] (There is only so much analog power available, and amplification adds noise.) Therefore, if the received analog signal is split up and sent into a large number of different signal combination circuits, it can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio of each.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] In MIMO communication systems with large number of antennas, so called massive MIMO systems, the beamforming algorithms executed at the digital baseband can get very complex.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] In addition, if all beamforming is done at baseband, each antenna needs its own RF feed.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] At high frequencies and with large number of antenna elements, this can be very costly, and increase loss and complexity in the system.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] To remedy these issues, hybrid beamforming has been suggested where some of the beamforming is done using analog components and not digital.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] There are many possible different functions that can be performed using analog components instead of at the digital baseband.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Beamforming, whether done digitally, or by means of analog architecture, has recently been applied in Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC), also known as Joint Communication and Sensing (JCAS), technology.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] For instance, a beamformer was suggested, in imperfect channel state information situations to perform communication tasks, while at the same time performing target detection to sense targets in the scene.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Beamforming can be used to try to extract sound sources in a room, such as multiple speakers in the cocktail party problem.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] This requires the locations of the speakers to be known in advance, for example by using the time of arrival from the sources to mics in the array, and inferring the locations from the distances.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Compared to carrier-wave telecommunications, natural audio contains a variety of frequencies.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] It is advantageous to separate frequency bands prior to beamforming because different frequencies have different optimal beamform filters (and hence can be treated as separate problems, in parallel, and then recombined afterward).
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Properly isolating these bands involves specialized non-standard filter banks.
[src:radio-access-network/beamforming] Instead, filters can be designed in which only local frequencies are detected by each channel (while retaining the recombination property to be able to reconstruct the original signal), and these are typically non-orthogonal unlike the FFT basis.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Traditional cellular, or Radio Access Networks (RAN), consist of many stand-alone base stations (BTS).
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Each BTS covers a small area, whereas a group BTS provides coverage over a continuous area.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Each BTS processes and transmits its own signal to and from the mobile terminal, and forwards the data payload to and from the mobile terminal and out to the core network via the backhaul.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Each BTS has its own cooling, back haul transportation, backup battery, monitoring system, and so on.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Because of limited spectral resources, network operators 'reuse' the frequency among different base stations, which can cause interference between neighboring cells.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] There are several limitations in the traditional cellular architecture.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] First, each BTS is costly to build and operate.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Moore's law helps reduce the size and power of an electrical system, but the supporting facilities of the BTS are not improved quite as well.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Second, when more BTS are added to a system to improve its capacity, interference among BTS is more severe as BTS are closer to each other and more of them are using the same frequency.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Third, because users are mobile, the traffic of each BTS fluctuates (called 'tide effect'), and as a result, the average utilization rate of individual BTS is pretty low.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] However, these processing resources cannot be shared with other BTS.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Therefore, all BTS are designed to handle the maximum traffic, not average traffic, resulting in a waste of processing resources and power at idle times.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] In the 1G and 2G cellular networks, base stations had an all-in-one architecture.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Analog, digital, and power functions were housed in a single cabinet as large as a refrigerator.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Usually the base station cabinet was placed in a dedicated room along with all necessary supporting facilitates such as power, backup battery, air conditioning, environment surveillance, and backhaul transmission equipment.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] The RF signal is generated by the base station RF unit and propagates through pairs of RF cables up to the antennas on the top of a base station tower or other mounting points.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] This all-in-one architecture was mostly found in macro cell deployments.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] For 3G, a distributed base station architecture was introduced by Ericsson, Nokia, Huawei, and other leading telecom equipment vendors.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] In this architecture the radio function unit, also known as the remote radio head (RRH), is separated from the digital function unit, or baseband unit (BBU) by fiber.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Digital baseband signals are carried over fiber, using the Open Base Station Architecture Initiative (OBSAI) or Common Public Radio Interface (CPRI) standard.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] The RRH can be installed on the top of tower close to the antenna, reducing the loss compared to the traditional base station where the RF signal has to travel through a long cable from the base station cabinet to the antenna at the top of the tower.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] The fiber link between RRH and BBU also allows more flexibility in network planning and deployment as they can be placed a few hundred meters or a few kilometers away.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Most modern base stations now use this decoupled architecture.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] C-RAN may be viewed as an architectural evolution of the above distributed base station system.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] It takes advantage of many technological advances in wireless, optical and IT communications systems.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] For example, it uses the latest CPRI standard, low cost Coarse or Dense Wavelength Division Multiplexing (CWDM/ DWDM) technology, and mmWave to allow transmission of baseband signal over long distance thus achieving large scale centralised base station deployment.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] It applies recent Data Centre Network technology to allow a low cost, high reliability, low latency and high bandwidth interconnect network in the BBU pool.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] It utilizes open platforms and real-time virtualization technology rooted in cloud computing to achieve dynamic shared resource allocation and support multi-vendor, multi-technology environments.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Native support to Collaborative Radio technologies: Any BBU can talk with any other BBU within the BBU pool with very high bandwidth (10 Gbit/s and above) and low latency (10 μs level).
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] This is enabled by the interconnection of BBUs in the pool.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] This is one major difference from BBU Hotelling, or base station Hotelling; in the latter case, the BBUs of different base stations are simply stacked together and have no direct link between them to allow physical layer co-ordination.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Real-time virtualization capability based on open platform: This is different from traditional base stations built on proprietary hardware, where the software and hardware are close-sourced and provided by single vendors.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] In contrast, a C-RAN BBU pool is built on open hardware, like x86/ARM CPU based servers, and interface cards that handle fiber links to RRHs and inter-connections in the pool.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Real-time virtualization ensures that resources in the pool can be allocated dynamically to base station software stacks, say 4G/3G/2G function modules from different vendors, according to network load.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] However, to satisfy the strict timing requirements of wireless communication systems, the real-time performance for C-RAN is at the level of tens of microseconds, which is two orders of magnitude better than the millisecond level 'real-time' performance usually seen in Cloud Computing environments.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] KT, a telecom operator in the Republic of Korea, introduced a Cloud Computing Center (CCC) system in their 3G (WCDMA/HSPA) and 4G (LTE/LTE-A) network in 2011 and 2012.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] The concept of CCC is basically the same as C-RAN.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] SK Telecom has also deployed Smart Cloud Access Network (SCAN) and Advanced-SCAN in their 4G (LTE/LTE-A) network in Korea no later than 2012.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] In 2014, Airvana (now CommScope) introduced OneCell, a C-RAN-based small cell system designed for enterprises and public spaces.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] One major alternative solution that is addressing similar challenges of RAN, is the small size, all-in-one outdoor BTS.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Thanks to the achievements in the semiconductor industry, all the functionality of a BTS, including RF, baseband processing, MAC processing and package level processing, can now be implemented in a volume of <50 liters.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] This makes the system small and weatherproof, reduces the difficulty of BTS site choice and construction, eliminates the air conditioning requirement, and thus reduces operational costs.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] However, because each BTS is still working on its own, it cannot readily make use of the collaboration algorithms to reduce the interference between neighboring BTSs.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] It is also relatively hard to upgrade or repair because the all-in-one BTS units are usually mounted near the antenna.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] More processing units in less-protected environments also implies a higher failure rate compared to C-RAN, which only has the RRU deployed outdoors.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] The advantage of Cloud RAN lies in its ability to implement LTE-Advanced features such as Coordinated MultiPoint (CoMP) with very low latency between multiple radio heads.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] However, the economic benefit of improvements such as CoMP can be negated by the higher backhaul costs for some operators.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] The main competition between small cell and C-RAN occurs in two deployment scenarios: outdoor hotspot coverage and indoor coverage.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] As one of the promising evolution paths for future cellular network architecture, C-RAN has attracted high academic research interest.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Meanwhile, because the native support of cooperative radio capability built into the C-RAN architecture, it also enables many advanced algorithms that were hard to implement in cellular networks, including Cooperative Multi-Point Transmission/Receiving, Network Coding, etc.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] In October 2011, Wireless World Research Forum 27 was hosted in Germany, when China Mobile was invited to give a C-RAN presentation.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] In August 2012, IEEE C-RAN 2012 workshop was hosted in Kunming, China.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] CRC Press published a book, "Green Communications: Theoretical Fundamentals, Algorithms and Applications", and has as its 11th chapter: "C-RAN: A Green RAN Framework".
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] In December 2012, an IEEE GlobalCom 2012 conference, International Workshop on Cloud Based-Stations and Large-Scale Cooperative Communications, was hosted in California, USA.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] The European Committee Frame Project 7 has sponsors and is currently addressing many problems related to cellular network architecture evolution.
[src:radio-access-network/c-ran] Many of these projects have taken C-RAN as one of the future cellular network architectures, like the Mobile Cloud Network project.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In telecommunications, **Long Term Evolution** (**LTE**) is a standard for wireless broadband communication for cellular mobile devices and data terminals.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] It is considered to be a "transitional" 4G technology, and is therefore also referred to as **3.95G** as a step above 3G.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] LTE is based on the 2G GSM/EDGE and 3G UMTS/HSPA standards.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] It improves on those standards' capacity and speed by using a different radio interface and core network improvements.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] LTE is the upgrade path for carriers with both GSM/UMTS networks and CDMA2000 networks.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] LTE has been succeeded by LTE Advanced, which is officially defined as a "true" 4G technology and also named "LTE+".
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The standard is developed by the 3GPP (3rd Generation Partnership Project) and is specified in its Release 8 document series, with minor enhancements described in Release 9.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] LTE is also called **3.95G** and has been marketed as **4G LTE** and **Advanced 4G**; but the original version did not meet the technical criteria of a 4G wireless service, as specified in the 3GPP Release 8 and 9 document series for LTE Advanced.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The LTE Advanced standard formally satisfies the ITU-R requirements for being considered IMT-Advanced.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] To differentiate LTE Advanced and WiMAX-Advanced from the then current 4G technologies, ITU has defined in January 2012 the latter as "True 4G".
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] LTE stands for Long Term Evolution and is a registered trademark owned by ETSI (European Telecommunications Standards Institute) for the wireless data communications technology and development of the GSM/UMTS standards.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] However, other nations and companies do play an active role in the LTE project.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The goal of LTE was to increase the capacity and speed of wireless data networks using new DSP (digital signal processing) techniques and modulations that were developed around the turn of the millennium.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] A further goal was the redesign and simplification of the network architecture to an IP-based system with significantly reduced transfer latency compared with the 3G architecture.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The LTE wireless interface is incompatible with 2G and 3G networks, so it must be operated on a separate radio spectrum.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The idea of LTE was first proposed in 1998, with the use of the COFDM radio access technique to replace the CDMA and studying its Terrestrial use in the L band at 1428 MHz (TE) In 2004 by Japan's NTT Docomo, with studies on the standard officially commenced in 2005.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In May 2007, the LTE/SAE Trial Initiative (LSTI) alliance was founded as a global collaboration between vendors and operators with the goal of verifying and promoting the new standard to ensure the global introduction of the technology as quickly as possible.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The LTE standard was finalized in December 2008, and the first publicly available LTE service was launched by TeliaSonera in Oslo and Stockholm on December 14, 2009, as a data connection with a USB modem.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In Canada, Rogers Wireless was the first to launch LTE network on July 7, 2011, offering the Sierra Wireless AirCard 313U USB mobile broadband modem, known as the "LTE Rocket stick" then followed closely by mobile devices from both HTC and Samsung.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The next version of LTE is LTE Advanced, which was standardized in March 2011.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Additional evolution known as LTE Advanced Pro was approved in 2015.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The LTE specification provides downlink peak rates of 300 Mbit/s, uplink peak rates of 75 Mbit/s, and QoS provisions permitting a transfer latency of less than 5 ms in the radio access network.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] LTE has the ability to manage fast-moving mobiles and supports multicast and broadcast streams.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] LTE supports scalable carrier bandwidths, from 1.4 MHz to 20 MHz and supports both frequency division duplexing (FDD) and time-division duplexing (TDD).
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The IP-based network architecture, called the Evolved Packet Core (EPC) designed to replace the GPRS Core Network, supports seamless handovers for both voice and data to cell towers with older network technology such as GSM, UMTS and CDMA2000.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The simpler architecture results in lower operating costs (for example, each E-UTRA cell will support up to four times the data and voice capacity supported by HSPA).
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Because LTE frequencies and bands differ from country to country, only multi-band phones can use LTE in all countries where it is supported.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Most carriers supporting GSM or HSUPA networks can be expected to upgrade their networks to LTE at some stage.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The following is a list of the top 10 countries/territories by 4G LTE coverage as measured by OpenSignal.com in February/March 2019.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] For the complete list of all the countries/territories, see list of countries by 4G LTE penetration.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] There are two major differences between LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD: how data is uploaded and downloaded, and what frequency spectra the networks are deployed in.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] While LTE-FDD uses paired frequencies to upload and download data, LTE-TDD uses a single frequency, alternating between uploading and downloading data through time.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The ratio between uploads and downloads on a LTE-TDD network can be changed dynamically, depending on whether more data needs to be sent or received.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD also operate on different frequency bands, with LTE-TDD working better at higher frequencies, and LTE-FDD working better at lower frequencies.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Frequencies used for LTE-TDD range from 1850 MHz to 3800 MHz, with several different bands being used.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The LTE-TDD spectrum is generally cheaper to access, and has less traffic.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Further, the bands for LTE-TDD overlap with those used for WiMAX, which can easily be upgraded to support LTE-TDD.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Despite the differences in how the two types of LTE handle data transmission, LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD share 90 percent of their core technology, making it possible for the same chipsets and networks to use both versions of LTE.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] A number of companies produce dual-mode chips or mobile devices, including Samsung and Qualcomm, while operators CMHK and Hi3G Access have developed dual-mode networks in Hong Kong and Sweden, respectively.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The creation of LTE-TDD involved a coalition of international companies that worked to develop and test the technology.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] China Mobile was an early proponent of LTE-TDD, along with other companies like Datang Telecom and Huawei, which worked to deploy LTE-TDD networks, and later developed technology allowing LTE-TDD equipment to operate in white spaces—frequency spectra between broadcast TV stations.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Intel also participated in the development, setting up a LTE-TDD interoperability lab with Huawei in China, as well as ST-Ericsson, Nokia, and Nokia Siemens (now Nokia Solutions and Networks), which developed LTE-TDD base stations that increased capacity by 80 percent and coverage by 40 percent.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Qualcomm also participated, developing the world's first multi-mode chip, combining both LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD, along with HSPA and EV-DO.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Accelleran, a Belgian company, has also worked to build small cells for LTE-TDD networks.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Trials of LTE-TDD technology began as early as 2010, with Reliance Industries and Ericsson India conducting field tests of LTE-TDD in India, achieving 80 megabit-per second download speeds and 20 megabit-per-second upload speeds.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] By 2011, China Mobile began trials of the technology in six cities.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Although initially seen as a technology utilized by only a few countries, including China and India, by 2011 international interest in LTE-TDD had expanded, especially in Asia, in part due to LTE-TDD's lower cost of deployment compared to LTE-FDD.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] By the middle of that year, 26 networks around the world were conducting trials of the technology.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The Global LTve (GTI) was also started in 2011, with founding partners China Mobile, Bharti Airtel, SoftBank Mobile, Vodafone, Clearwire, Aero2 and E-Plus.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In September 2011, Huawei announced it would partner with Polish mobile provider Aero2 to develop a combined LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD network in Poland, and by April 2012, ZTE Corporation had worked to deploy trial or commercial LTE-TDD networks for 33 operators in 19 countries.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In late 2012, Qualcomm worked extensively to deploy a commercial LTE-TDD network in India, and partnered with Bharti Airtel and Huawei to develop the first multi-mode LTE-TDD smartphone for India.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In Japan, SoftBank Mobile launched LTE-TDD services in February 2012 under the name **Advanced eXtended Global Platform** (AXGP), and marketed as SoftBank 4G (ja).
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The AXGP band was previously used for Willcom's PHS service, and after PHS was discontinued in 2010 the PHS band was re-purposed for AXGP service.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In the U.S., Clearwire planned to implement LTE-TDD, with chipmaker Qualcomm agreeing to support Clearwire's frequencies on its multi-mode LTE chipsets.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] With Sprint's acquisition of Clearwire in 2013, the carrier began using these frequencies for LTE service on networks built by Samsung, Alcatel-Lucent, and Nokia.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] As of March 2013, 156 commercial 4G LTE networks existed, including 142 LTE-FDD networks and 14 LTE-TDD networks.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] As of November 2013, the South Korean government planned to allow a fourth wireless carrier in 2014, which would provide LTE-TDD services, and in December 2013, LTE-TDD licenses were granted to China's three mobile operators, allowing commercial deployment of 4G LTE services.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In January 2014, Nokia Solutions and Networks indicated that it had completed a series of tests of voice over LTE (VoLTE) calls on China Mobile's TD-LTE network.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The next month, Nokia Solutions and Networks and Sprint announced that they had demonstrated throughput speeds of 2.6 gigabits per second using a LTE-TDD network, surpassing the previous record of 1.6 gigabits per second.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Much of the LTE standard addresses the upgrading of 3G UMTS to what will eventually be 4G mobile communications technology.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] A large amount of the work is aimed at simplifying the architecture of the system, as it transitions from the existing UMTS circuit + packet switching combined network to an all-IP flat architecture system.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The LTE standard supports only packet switching with its all-IP network.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Voice calls in GSM, UMTS, and CDMA2000 are circuit switched, so with the adoption of LTE, carriers will have to re-engineer their voice call network.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In this approach, LTE just provides data services, and when a voice call is to be initiated or received, it will fall back to the circuit-switched domain.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] , and therefore, can provide services quickly.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] However, the disadvantage is a longer call setup delay.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] In this approach, the handset works simultaneously in the LTE and circuit-switched modes, with the LTE mode providing data services and the circuit-switched mode providing the voice service.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The disadvantage of this solution is that the phone can become expensive with high power consumption.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] One additional approach that is not initiated by operators is the usage of over-the-top content (OTT) services, using applications like Skype and Google Talk to provide LTE voice service.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Most major backers of LTE preferred and promoted VoLTE from the beginning.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The lack of software support in initial LTE devices, as well as core network devices, however, led to a number of carriers promoting VoLGA (Voice over LTE Generic Access) as an interim solution.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] The idea was to use the same principles as GAN (Generic Access Network, also known as UMA or Unlicensed Mobile Access), which defines the protocols through which a mobile handset can perform voice calls over a customer's private Internet connection, usually over wireless LAN.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] VoLGA however never gained much support, because VoLTE (IMS) promises much more flexible services, albeit at the cost of having to upgrade the entire voice call infrastructure.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] VoLTE may require Single Radio Voice Call Continuity (SRVCC) to be able to smoothly perform a handover to a 2G or 3G network in case of poor LTE signal quality.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] While the industry has standardized on VoLTE, early LTE deployments required carriers to introduce circuit-switched fallback as a stopgap measure.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] When placing or receiving a voice call on a non-VoLTE-enabled network or device, LTE handsets will fall back to old 2G or 3G networks for the duration of the call.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] To ensure compatibility, 3GPP demands at least AMR-NB codec (narrow band), but the recommended speech codec for VoLTE is Adaptive Multi-Rate Wideband, also known as HD Voice.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] This codec is mandated in 3GPP networks that support 16 kHz sampling.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Fraunhofer IIS has proposed and demonstrated "Full-HD Voice", an implementation of the AAC-ELD (Advanced Audio Coding – Enhanced Low Delay) codec for LTE handsets.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Where previous cell phone voice codecs only supported frequencies up to 3.5 kHz and upcoming wideband audio services branded as *HD Voice* up to 7 kHz, Full-HD Voice supports the entire bandwidth range from 20 Hz to 20 kHz.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] For end-to-end Full-HD Voice calls to succeed, however, both the caller's and recipient's handsets, as well as networks, have to support the feature.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] As a result, phones from one country may not work in other countries.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] Users will need a multi-band capable phone for roaming internationally.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] According to the European Telecommunications Standards Institute's (ETSI) intellectual property rights (IPR) database, about 50 companies have declared, as of March 2012, holding essential patents covering the LTE standard.
[src:radio-access-network/lte-telecommunication] This is less than the combined published rates, due to reduced-rate licensing agreements, such as cross-licensing.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] MU-MIMO extends single-user MIMO (SU-MIMO), where one multi-antenna transmitter communicates with one multi-antenna receiver.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] It is closely related to space-division multiple access (SDMA), because users are separated by their spatial channel characteristics rather than only by time, frequency, or code resources.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] MU-MIMO is used in cellular networks and wireless LAN systems, and is related to techniques such as massive MIMO, coordinated multipoint transmission and reception (CoMP), and cooperative MIMO.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] In SU-MIMO, the antennas used for spatial multiplexing usually belong to one transmitter and one receiver.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] In MU-MIMO, the spatial streams may be assigned to different users.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] This can increase system throughput when the users have sufficiently distinct channel conditions.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] The performance of MU-MIMO depends on the number of antennas, the accuracy of channel state information, scheduling, interference management, and the signal-processing techniques used at the transmitter and receiver.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] The **MIMO broadcast channel** describes a downlink system in which one multi-antenna transmitter sends data to multiple receivers.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] In wireless networks, this transmitter is commonly a base station or access point.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] Downlink MU-MIMO usually requires the transmitter to have channel state information at the transmitter (CSIT).
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] This information is used for user scheduling, beamforming, and precoding.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] If the transmitter has accurate CSIT, it can direct different spatial streams toward different users while reducing interference between them.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] Precoding methods for the MIMO broadcast channel include dirty paper coding, zero-forcing precoding, block diagonalization, and other linear or hybrid precoding techniques.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] The **MIMO multiple-access channel** describes an uplink system in which multiple users transmit to one multi-antenna receiver.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] In cellular systems, the receiver is usually a base station; in wireless local-area networks, it may be an access point.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] Uplink MU-MIMO relies on receiver-side processing to separate the users' signals.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] Techniques include joint detection, interference cancellation, and SDMA-based scheduling.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] Channel state information at the receiver (CSIR) is typically obtained from uplink pilot or reference signals.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] Compared with downlink CSIT, receiver-side channel estimation is often simpler because the receiver can directly estimate the channels from the transmitted pilots.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] MIMO MAC systems can outperform point-to-point MIMO systems when the receiver has enough antennas and processing capability to separate signals from multiple users.
[src:radio-access-network/multi-user-mimo] Several wireless technologies are closely related to MU-MIMO.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] A **radio access network** (**RAN**) is part of a mobile telecommunication system implementing a radio access technology (RAT).
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] Conceptually, it resides between a device such as a mobile phone, a computer, or any remotely controlled machine and provides connection with its core network (CN).
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] Depending on the standard, mobile phones and other wireless connected devices are varyingly known as user equipment (UE), terminal equipment, mobile station (MS), etc.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] RAN functionality is typically provided by a silicon chip residing in both the core network as well as the user equipment.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] It is also possible for a single handset/phone to be simultaneously connected to multiple RANs.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] Handsets capable of this are sometimes called dual-mode handsets.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] For instance it is common for handsets to support both GSM and UMTS (a.k.a.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] Such devices seamlessly transfer an ongoing call between different radio access networks without the user noticing any disruption in service.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] According to research company New Street, mobile providers T-Mobile US and AT&T use Swedish communication company Ericsson as their primary RAN provider, while Verizon primarily uses South Korean provider Samsung.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] Nokia is the minority vendor for all major US wireless providers.
[src:radio-access-network/radio-access-network] According to EJL Wireless Research, Verizon is also using Ericsson.
